<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Original description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
From 
<bibRefCitation author="Lowe, RT" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Cambridge Philosophical Society" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" pagination="1 - 70" title="Primitiae faunae et florae Maderae et Portus Sancti; sive species quaedam novae vel hactenus minus rite cognitae animalium et plantarum in his insulis degentium breviter descriptae." volume="4" year="1831">Lowe 1831</bibRefCitation>
: H. testa parvula, conoidea, sub-pyramidata, depressiuscula, supra planulata, perforata, carinata, tota scaberrima, fusca, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="suprà">supra</normalizedToken>
fasciata: spira pyramidata elevata; sutura distincta, impressa; anfractibus convexis; ultimi carina acuta, distincta, supra marginata sc. sulco expressa vel exarata; omnibus granulis distinctissimis, conferitis, asperrimis scobinatis et quasi echinulatis; umbilicus parvo, sub-spirali, aperto; apertura rotundata; peristomate continuo, circinato, disjuncto, reflexo. Axis 2 lin. Diam. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="2½">21/2</normalizedToken>
. Anfr. 6.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="diagnostic features of the shell">
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Diagnostic features of the shell.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Shell as in the genus description. The main diagnostic feature is the presence of only one keel along the body whorl. The overall shape of the shell of 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. echinulata" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species" species="echinulata">H. echinulata</taxonomicName>
is always conical but not scalariform as in 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. bicarinata" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species" species="bicarinata">H. bicarinata</taxonomicName>
. The whorls are rounded and lack the typical 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“shoulder”">&quot;shoulder&quot;</normalizedToken>
. The sutures are deep, but less deeply marked than in 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. bicarinata" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species" species="bicarinata">H. bicarinata</taxonomicName>
(see Figs 79-82).
</paragraph>
