<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="status and conservation">
<paragraph pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Status and conservation.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
According to 
<bibRefCitation pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Seddon (2011b)</bibRefCitation>
the species is Least Concern (LC), but in our opinion, the species should be considered as Endangered (EN B1a, b(i, ii, iv), 2a, b(i, ii, iv)) because its area of occupancy and extent of occurrence is less than 8 km2 and because it is mostly restricted to the highest elevations in the north-eastern part of Porto Santo and only occurs at scattered and isolated places with suitably humid microclimates. Mayor threats to the species include an observed decline of suitable habitats, extent of occurrence and area of occupancy over the past 30 years, i.e. as the result of longer drought periods which are possibly associated with effects of climate change, an increase of fire incidents, grazing by goats and to a lesser extent also hiking as tourism is increasing on Porto Santo. As most of the known localities are concentrated in the Pico Branco-Terra 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Chã">Cha</normalizedToken>
area in the north-easternmost part of Porto Santo (Fig. 94), we consider that the species is not present at more than five locations.
</paragraph>
